@node Session management
@section Session management

@findex codex
@findex codex-start-in-directory
@findex codex-resume
@findex codex-fork
@findex codex-new-instance
@findex codex-kill
@findex codex-kill-all

The command @code{codex} starts a Codex instance in the current project root or, if not in a project, in the directory of the current file.  If a Codex instance is already running for that directory, you are prompted for an instance name so that multiple instances can coexist.  With a single prefix argument (@samp{C-u}), the cursor switches to the Codex buffer after starting.  With a double prefix argument (@samp{C-u C-u}), you are prompted for the project directory.

The command @code{codex-start-in-directory} always prompts for a directory before starting Codex, regardless of the current project.  With a prefix argument, it also switches to the Codex buffer.

The command @code{codex-resume} resumes a previous Codex session by running @code{codex resume}.  If other instances already exist for the directory, you are prompted for an instance name; otherwise the name defaults to @samp{"default"}.  With a prefix argument, it passes @code{--last} to resume the most recent session.

The command @code{codex-fork} forks a previous session by running @code{codex fork}.  Like @code{codex-resume}, it only prompts for an instance name when other instances exist, and accepts a prefix argument for @code{--last}.

The command @code{codex-new-instance} creates a new Codex instance and always prompts for an instance name, even if no other instances are running.  This is useful when you want to name your instance from the start.  It accepts the same prefix argument conventions as @code{codex}.

The command @code{codex-kill} kills the Codex instance associated with the current directory.  If multiple instances are running for the directory, you are prompted to select one.  If @code{codex-confirm-kill} is non-nil (the default), confirmation is required.

The command @code{codex-kill-all} kills all Codex instances across all directories.  It reports the number of instances killed and, like @code{codex-kill}, respects the @code{codex-confirm-kill} setting.

@node Sending commands and context
@section Sending commands and context

@findex codex-send-command
@findex codex-send-command-with-context
@findex codex-send-region
@findex codex-send-buffer-file
@findex codex-send-image
@findex codex-fix-error-at-point

The command @code{codex-send-command} reads a command from the minibuffer and sends it to the Codex instance for the current project.  Input history is maintained in @code{codex-command-history}.  With a prefix argument, the cursor switches to the Codex buffer after sending.

The command @code{codex-send-command-with-context} works like @code{codex-send-command} but appends a file reference (in @code{@@file:line} format) to the command.  If a region is active, it includes the line range of the region.  This is particularly useful when you want to direct Codex's attention to a specific location in your code.

The command @code{codex-send-region} sends the active region to Codex, or the entire buffer if no region is active.  With a single prefix argument, it prompts for instructions to prepend to the text.  With a double prefix argument, it also switches to the Codex buffer.

The command @code{codex-send-buffer-file} sends the file path of the current buffer to Codex, prefixed with @code{@@}.  This tells Codex to read the file.  With a prefix argument, it prompts for instructions to include alongside the file reference.  With a double prefix argument, it also switches to the Codex buffer.

The command @code{codex-send-image} prompts for an image file and sends its path to Codex prefixed with @code{@@}.  Use this to attach screenshots or diagrams as context for your request.

The command @code{codex-fix-error-at-point} examines the error at point (using Flycheck or @code{help-at-pt}), formats it with the file and line reference, and sends it to Codex with instructions to fix the error.  With a prefix argument, it switches to the Codex buffer.

@node TUI key sequences
@section TUI key sequences

@findex codex-send-return
@findex codex-send-escape
@findex codex-edit-previous-message
@findex codex-queue-followup
@findex codex-inject-mid-turn
@findex codex-header-search
@findex codex-send-1
@findex codex-send-2
@findex codex-send-3

These commands send specific key sequences to the Codex TUI, allowing you to interact with Codex without switching to the terminal buffer.

The command @code{codex-send-return} sends a return key press.  This is equivalent to pressing @samp{Enter} in the Codex TUI and is often used to confirm actions.

The command @code{codex-send-escape} sends an escape key press, typically used to cancel or dismiss prompts.  In eat buffers, @samp{C-g} is also bound to this command.

The command @code{codex-edit-previous-message} sends @samp{Esc Esc} to walk back and edit the previous message.  After sending the sequence, it switches to the Codex buffer so you can edit inline.

The command @code{codex-queue-followup} sends a @samp{Tab} key press to queue a follow-up prompt while Codex is still working.

The command @code{codex-inject-mid-turn} sends a @samp{Return} key press to inject instructions while Codex is in the middle of processing.

The command @code{codex-header-search} sends @samp{Ctrl+K} to open the header search overlay in the Codex TUI@.

The commands @code{codex-send-1}, @code{codex-send-2}, and @code{codex-send-3} send the corresponding digit to the Codex TUI@.  These are useful for selecting numbered options in menus.

@node Buffer and window management
@section Buffer and window management

@findex codex-toggle
@findex codex-switch-to-buffer
@findex codex-select-buffer
@findex codex-toggle-read-only-mode

The command @code{codex-toggle} shows or hides the Codex window.  If the Codex buffer is currently visible, it deletes the window.  If it is hidden, it displays it using @code{codex-display-window-fn}.  The @code{codex-no-delete-other-windows} parameter is applied to the window.  If @code{codex-toggle-auto-select} is non-nil, focus moves to the Codex window when it is shown (@ref{Window management}).

The command @code{codex-switch-to-buffer} switches to the Codex buffer for the current project.  If multiple instances are running, you are prompted to select one.  With a prefix argument, it shows all Codex instances across all directories.

The command @code{codex-select-buffer} prompts you to select from all running Codex instances across all directories and switches to the selected one.

The command @code{codex-toggle-read-only-mode} toggles the terminal between read-only mode and interactive mode.  In read-only mode (eat's Emacs mode or vterm's copy mode), you can navigate and copy text using normal Emacs keybindings.  In interactive mode, keystrokes are sent to the terminal.

@node Model and permissions
@section Model and permissions

@findex codex-cycle-permissions

The command @code{codex-cycle-permissions} sends @samp{/permissions} to the Codex TUI to cycle through approval modes.

@node Diagnostics
@section Diagnostics

@findex codex-diagnose-faces-at-point
@findex codex-diagnose-faces-in-region
@findex codex-redraw

When the Codex buffer displays rendering artifacts --- such as colored rectangles with invisible text --- these diagnostic commands help identify the root cause by inspecting the face properties that the terminal emulator has applied.

The command @code{codex-diagnose-faces-at-point} reports the face plist at point, including the explicit and effective foreground and background colors, the WCAG contrast ratio between them, the @code{:inherit} chain, and whether the background remapping system would process this span.  Run this with point on a visually corrupted region to see whether the issue is a low-contrast color combination, a missing foreground, or a background that falls below the remapping threshold (@ref{Background and contrast remapping, , Background color remapping}).

The command @code{codex-diagnose-faces-in-region} audits all face property spans between BEG and END, reporting any non-whitespace text with a contrast ratio below 3:1.  With no active region, it audits the visible portion of the buffer.  The output lists the line number, contrast ratio, foreground, background, and a text excerpt for each problematic span.

The command @code{codex-redraw} asks the Codex TUI to repaint and then forces the Emacs terminal backend to redisplay.  It is bound to @code{C-l} in Codex buffers and to @code{l} in @code{codex-command-map}.  This is mainly a recovery command for existing or explicitly opted-in alt-screen sessions; new sessions avoid that failure class by default because @code{codex-use-alt-screen} is nil.

